I broke my wrist January 4th but even before then I was severely out of shape. I've also felt out of touch with myself. I used to take yoga in highschool (5 years ago) and I overcame my depression by meditating everyday and really finding myself in the daily yoga practices. My instructor really spoke to me and was the kindest, goofiest woman. But I haven't done yoga in many years and after breaking my wrist and being unable to do so many things for many months, I found myself needing to reconnect with my past self. So I started this challenge on whim and haven't stopped since. The first few days I could barely keep up, and now I was able to do the side plank on my healed wrist and I didn't struggle! I feel amazing. My wrist feels so good and strong. I had been so scared to lift and do things with my healed wrist, but not anymore. I look forward to building strength in it, seeing what I can. Been working through this series slowly as I try to keep my yoga schedule regular. Like a lot of people, I picked it back up due to the quarantine. Yesterday I did Day 15. Day 16 âœ”ï¸ I read a piece of wisdom today that many of us have probably heard before in different versions: "Only that which dies can renew itself." - J. Krishnamurti. As the days go by, I notice small sacrifices that I'm willing to make in order to improve myself. I'm able to say no (politely yes assertively) to people who don't contribute to others or commit to themselves. I guess it's a lot easier to be with people who are similar to us rather than otherwise. Sometimes, I'm really proud of the people and teachers around me, and sometimes not so much--and this is usually a direct reflection of how I feel on the inside! The gradual changes I'm making each day feels like parts of "old me dying" as I'm trying to renew myself. And with this community I feel like I'm on the right path. Namaste  ğŸ™

I should preface this by saying that I adore Adriene and her videos - she has gotten me back into yoga and I love seeing people's stories on here.  :)
However, her series is very different from other beginner yoga series I have done.  I wish that she would focus more on breathing, meditating, and slowly stretching into new poses rather than more of a fast-paced exercise yoga that this turns into sometimes.  Some of her videos are perfect and I don't mind getting a workout occasionally, but sometimes I come away feeling exhausted rather than energized.  I also find some things difficult for beginners.  For example I can't even touch my toes so the two moves she did with touching toes and putting hands under feet I couldn't do at all.  Also, at the end of her videos I would love for her to let some soft music play or lead her viewers into a meditation rather than ending it abruptly.

As a yogi recovering from a dislocated shoulder, I feel like this routine is a perfect light workout for rehabilitating shoulder stability, but remember to keep your shoulders "activated" or flexed during the side planks. Don't let that bottom shoulder fall into itself or it will really pull on your ligaments and soft tissue. If the side planks or planks in general are giving you trouble, check out an exercise called Turkish Get Up (TGU), it's fantastic for building the core strength that will make flowing through routines like this much more enjoyable. Just doing 5 a day with light weight (1-15 lbs) will yield incredible results with commitment. Namaste.
